attention calculation, is it essentially summing? how many mults vs adds?









great question. this is exactly where your determinism concerns hit hardest.

short answer:

attention is mostly dot products + softmax
dot products = lots of multiplies + lots of adds (sums)

so yes:

attention is heavily dominated by summation


⸻

🧠 break attention into steps

standard attention (single head):

Q, K, V

scores = Q × K^T
weights = softmax(scores)
output = weights × V


⸻

🔬 step-by-step math

1. Q × K^T (the big one)

this is matrix multiply

each element:

score[i,j] = sum over d of (Q[i,d] * K[j,d])

👉 this is:

d multiplies
d-1 adds

for EACH pair (i, j)

⸻

2. softmax

for each row:

softmax(x_i) = exp(x_i) / sum(exp(x))

operations per element:
	•	1 exp
	•	1 add (into sum)
	•	1 divide

👉 again:

sum of exp values = reduction = nondeterminism hotspot


⸻

3. weights × V

another matrix multiply:

output[i] = sum over j of (weights[i,j] * V[j])

same pattern:

many multiplies + many adds


⸻

📊 operation counts (important)

assume:
	•	sequence length = N
	•	embedding dim = D

⸻

Q × K^T

N × N outputs
each = D multiplies + D adds

total:

~ N² × D multiplies
~ N² × D adds


⸻

weights × V

N outputs
each = N × D work

total:

~ N² × D multiplies
~ N² × D adds


⸻

total attention cost

~ 2 × N² × D multiplies
~ 2 × N² × D adds

plus softmax overhead

⸻

🧠 key insight

multiplies ≈ adds (same order)

BUT:

adds are the problem for determinism

because:

sum order changes → result changes


⸻

🧨 where nondeterminism happens

1. dot product accumulation

sum(Q[i,d] * K[j,d])

this is:

reduction over D

→ order matters

⸻

2. softmax denominator

sum(exp(scores))

→ reduction again

⸻

3. output accumulation

sum(weights * V)

→ another reduction

⸻

👉 so attention has:

multiple nested reductions

this is why it’s one of the worst offenders for nondeterminism

⸻

⚡ how GPU actually computes this

not:

left to right sum

but:

parallel partial sums
then merged

example:

thread 1 sums chunk A
thread 2 sums chunk B
then combine A + B

👉 tree changes → result changes

⸻

🧠 your fixed-tree idea applied here

instead of:

sum arbitrary order

you want:

fixed reduction tree over D

like:

pairwise sum
then pairwise sum
...

that WOULD:

improve determinism

but:

slower + not what libraries do by default


⸻

⚡ deeper insight (important)

multiplies are stable

a * b = deterministic (given same bits)

adds are unstable

(a + b) + c ≠ a + (b + c)

so:

attention nondeterminism ≈ accumulation nondeterminism


⸻

🧨 beast takeaway

if you want deterministic attention:

you must control:

1. reduction order (critical)
2. precision (fp32 better than fp16)
3. kernel choice (no dynamic switching)


⸻

🧠 extreme version (reference mode)

you could implement:

deterministic dot product:
fixed chunking
fixed tree
fp32 accumulation

for:
	•	validation
	•	scientific runs

⸻

⚡ quick numbers example

say:

N = 512
D = 64

then:

ops ≈ 2 × 512² × 64
   ≈ 33 million multiplies
   ≈ 33 million adds

per attention layer

⸻

🧠 final mental model

attention = matrix multiply + softmax + matrix multiply

matrix multiply = multiply + sum
sum = the problem


⸻

final read

attention is:
heavy on multiplies
equally heavy on adds

but determinism problem is:
almost entirely from adds (reductions)


